It is becoming increasingly clear that different opinions are not tolerated in the Labour Party and each opinion is judged on whether it is acceptable for the leadership of the party.
This began shortly after Jeremy became the leader, as colleagues with whom I thought I had a similar political view began to expect me to change my mind and take positions that I would never agree with in other situations - either on national security or on the EU single market.
Whenever I speak publicly - and, in truth, it makes no difference what I say - I am followed by a social media abuse with a demand that they remove me from my post as MP, denounce the centre's politics, and tell me that I do not belong to the Labour Party.
And this is not just my experience.
Yes, I know that I have had more luck than some of my colleagues because the comments addressed to me tend to be political.
I admire the professionalism and determination of those colleagues who daily face a lot of sexual or racist abuse but are never hidden from comments.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this political era is the fact that levels of abuse have become normal.
Last week, Jeremy Corbyn said that the Labour Party should foster a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we are no longer that broad group and with every motion of "lack of confidence" or change in the rules of selection, the party becomes narrower.
I've been given a lot of advice over the last two years that has encouraged me to keep my opinions to myself, not to be so vocal and then everything "would be fine."
But I did not go into politics to do so.
Since I entered the Labour Party 32 years ago as a school pupil, provoked by the negligence of Thatcher's government that left my comprehensive school class literally in a disastrous state, I have sought to improve public services for those who need them most - either as a local councillor or as a government minister.
I've never lost my job, even in the last election.
No one in Nottingham East could have been, in any way, confused about my policy positions and areas of disagreement with the current leadership.
For those who promoted the motion on Friday, all I can say is that when the country is moving towards a Brexit that will harm our families, businesses and public services, I cannot understand the desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But in truth, the only message I have is not for Nottingham Momentum, it's for my constituents, whether members of the Labour Party or not: I'm proud to work for you and I promise you that no amount of threats that would take me out of my office or of political expediency would deter me from acting in all of them.
