North Korea says it will "in no way" unilaterally disarm without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were deepening its distrust of the United States and that there was no way the country would unilaterally abandon its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken "considerable goodwill measures" last year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and vowing not to proliferate nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding response from the United States," he said.
"Without any trust in the United States there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances we will in no way disarm ourselves unilaterally first."
While Repeating familiar complaints from North Korea about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization in which North Korea would have been rewarded as it took gradual steps, his statement appeared significantly to have not refused unthinking unilateral denuclearization as it had done at Pyongyang's past.
He referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between a serving U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work towards the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" while Trump vowed to "denuclearize the Korean peninsula."
North Korea was seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States said Pyongyang must first surrender its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to reduce tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on "denuclearization first" and increases the level of pressure through sanctions to achieve their goal in a coherent way, and even objects to the "declaration of an end to the war," said Ri.
"The perception that sanctions can break us is a dream of people who don't know about us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions are deepening our lack of trust."
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months and added: "If the party to this denuclearization issue had been South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come to such a blockade."
Despite this, Ri's tone of speech was dramatically different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting the US mainland with North Korean rockets was inevitable after "Mr. Cutthroat President" Trump called Kim a "rocket man" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said there was still a lot of work to be done and sanctions should remain in place until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a timeline for this, saying "If you take two, three years or five months - it doesn't make a difference."
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo, on Thursday, told the UN Security Council that: "Enforcement of Security Council sanctions should continue vigorously and without stopping until we realize fully and finally verified denuclearization."
The Security Council has unanimously strengthened sanctions on North Korea since 2006 with the aim of stopping funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met Ri in the margins of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, after within a few hours North Korea criticized him for making "gangster-like demands".
In a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea promised to dismantle a missile site as well as a nuclear complex if the United States takes "corresponding measures."
He said Kim had told him that the "corresponding measures" he was seeking were security guarantees that Trump had promised in Singapore and steps towards normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students make a course on taking enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has managed to make all of its undergraduate students sleep longer with the aim of fighting the growing macho culture of studying all night and staying awake thanks to caffeine.
An academic has found that university students in the first place in the world often have no idea about the real basics on how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, believing it to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after making a speech about the impact that sleeplessness had on learning.
"At last a girl came up to me and said, 'Why are they telling me this now, in my last year?'
She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which began for the first time this year, explains to students the essentials on how good sleep traditions help academic and athletic performance, as well as improving their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students had serious insomnia during the week.
The one-hour course involves a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a students' bedroom, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, trainers and books to tell them the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance would have an effect from a sleep deficiency, and the importance of routine.
In another section, participants are told how long-term insomnia can increase the risks of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
Then, a campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it will not change the behavior of students right away.
But we believe they have a right to know - as much as you have a right to know the health effects when you choose to smoke cigarettes," added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of being proud to "have managed to stay up all night studying" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students meant that lack of sleep was a growing problem.
Ensuring that you sleep enough, and of good quality, should be a student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, severe fatigue and anxiety, he said - also to avoid gaining weight, since insomnia puts the brain in a mode of hunger, which makes them hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California, who is studying chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having attended one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to insist on a course throughout the campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduating students to do a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Prof. Czeisler recommended that students should consider making an alarm for when they go to sleep, as well as when they wake up, and know about the harmful effects of "blue light" emanating from electronic screens and LED light, which can balance your circadian rhythm, leading to trouble sleeping.
